folder: Troutman Street & Seneca Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Troutman Street (foreground), at Seneca Ave. (Note that both these streets when constructed will appear in the foreground in line of barn partially seen at the left of view. This is a set of two views showing rears of the Covert Jenkins farmhouse facing on Flushing Ave. (No. 1410). It was the property of J.G. Jenkins in 1869.

1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Troutman Street & Seneca Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Troutman Street (foreground, under construction), at Seneca Ave; viewed northwestward. In the right foreground is the barn of Covert-Jenkins and also a partial view of their house. In front of the factory building (white) is the barn of Peter Wyckoff and on the right of it is the house. Flushing Avenue extends in both directions along a picket fence,  seen beyond sunken barn in foreground. The left buildings in the background are on the west side of Cypress Ave. (arbitrarily set) north and south of Troutman Street in Brooklyn.

April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
